1
00:00:01,492 --> 00:00:02,705
[CREATURE GROWLING ON-SCREEN]

2
00:00:02,788 --> 00:00:04,167
[WOMAN SCREAMS ON-SCREEN]

3
00:00:05,004 --> 00:00:07,762
[JUGHEAD] <i>One distinct advantage
of dating an owner of a movie theater</i>

4
00:00:07,846 --> 00:00:10,521
<i>is getting to see flicks
with my pals for free,</i>

5
00:00:10,605 --> 00:00:12,611
<i>which is why every Tuesday night</i>

6
00:00:12,694 --> 00:00:16,958
<i>we would gather to watch whatever latest
Atomic Age fright-fest was playing,</i>

7
00:00:17,042 --> 00:00:18,964
<i>little imagining
that we would soon be walking</i>

8
00:00:19,048 --> 00:00:23,855
<i>into our very own real-life
science-fiction-tinged B-movie.</i>

9
00:00:23,938 --> 00:00:25,944
[OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING]

10
00:00:27,324 --> 00:00:31,044
<i>There, suddenly,
was a melting man coming towards us,</i>

11
00:00:31,128 --> 00:00:34,639
<i>looking like a wax statue that had been
left out in the sun too long.</i>

12
00:00:35,893 --> 00:00:38,025
<i>At which point the cavalry
suddenly arrived.</i>

13
00:00:38,610 --> 00:00:40,784
[GUNFIRE]

14
00:00:46,008 --> 00:00:49,102
<i>Sheriff Keller would soon be claiming
the man was a vagrant,</i>

15
00:00:49,185 --> 00:00:53,700
<i>suffering from a rare case of...
Wait for it... leprosy.</i>

16
00:00:53,783 --> 00:00:57,085
<i>But that didn't jibe with what
I overheard Ethel say to Ben Button.</i>

17
00:00:57,169 --> 00:01:00,680
He's wearing the same uniform my dad did
when he worked at the maple factory.

18
00:01:01,182 --> 00:01:04,610
[JUGHEAD] <i>Once again, there was
something rotten in the town of Riverdale.</i>

19
00:01:04,693 --> 00:01:06,909
<i>And if I was going to get
real answers this time,</i>

20
00:01:06,992 --> 00:01:08,873
<i>I'd have to hunt them down myself.</i>

21
00:01:09,876 --> 00:01:13,429
<i>Luckily, I knew for a fact
that the town coroner, Dr. Curdle,</i>

22
00:01:13,513 --> 00:01:17,316
<i>was a fan of Pep's horror comics,
which were hard to come by now</i>

23
00:01:17,399 --> 00:01:19,365
<i>unless you had
an inside connection like me.</i>

24
00:01:19,448 --> 00:01:23,210
Oh, yes.
These are quite marvelous, Mr. Jones.

25
00:01:24,924 --> 00:01:27,306
Worthy of a quid pro quo.

26
00:01:27,390 --> 00:01:31,737
Keen-o. So clue me in on what you know
about that mysterious melting man.

27
00:01:31,821 --> 00:01:33,577
How did he end up looking that way?

28
00:01:35,374 --> 00:01:38,216
He was suffering
from acute radiation poisoning.

29
00:01:39,261 --> 00:01:40,557
[WHISTLES]

30
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:43,650
Jeepers. Nuclear or atomic?

31
00:01:44,486 --> 00:01:46,409
And where would he get
radiation poisoning?

32
00:01:46,994 --> 00:01:51,007
I couldn't say. Unfortunately,
I didn't have much time with the body

33
00:01:51,090 --> 00:01:53,724
before Mayor Blossom claimed it
and whisked it away.

34
00:01:53,807 --> 00:01:56,650
The melting man, as you call him,

35
00:01:57,276 --> 00:02:00,035
was an employee
of the mayor's maple factory,

36
00:02:00,119 --> 00:02:01,874
is my understanding.

37
00:02:02,627 --> 00:02:04,466
That stinks like a rotten fish.

38
00:02:09,231 --> 00:02:11,572
Ethel, are you ready to walk to school?

39
00:02:12,199 --> 00:02:15,668
Betty, are you sure you don't want
your mom to drive you and Ethel to school?

40
00:02:16,504 --> 00:02:19,221
Under no circumstances.
Ethel, come on. We're gonna be late.

41
00:02:19,304 --> 00:02:20,308
[ALICE] Don't worry, Hal.

42
00:02:21,019 --> 00:02:22,858
One day, it'll be raining cats and dogs,

43
00:02:22,941 --> 00:02:25,450
and she'll finally let me give her a ride.

44
00:02:25,533 --> 00:02:26,704
Mm, no, I won't.

45
00:02:26,787 --> 00:02:30,382
Ethel, Veronica, and I signed up
for driver's education at school,

46
00:02:30,466 --> 00:02:32,723
so pretty soon
I'll be driving myself wherever I want.

47
00:02:32,806 --> 00:02:34,812
[INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING]

48
00:02:41,542 --> 00:02:44,803
Great news from Coach Parsley
over at Camp Evans.

49
00:02:45,471 --> 00:02:47,353
You are in, Reggie.

50
00:02:48,606 --> 00:02:50,613
- No fooling, coach?
- In where?

51
00:02:50,696 --> 00:02:55,169
Only the best summer basketball camp
for high schoolers in the country.

52
00:02:56,004 --> 00:02:58,721
That's wonderful news.
Congratulations, Reggie.

53
00:02:58,806 --> 00:03:01,982
What about you, Bill Shakespeare?
What are your plans?

54
00:03:03,278 --> 00:03:05,577
No summer camp for poetry, is there?

55
00:03:05,660 --> 00:03:08,294
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

56
00:03:09,756 --> 00:03:12,975
There will be plenty
for Archie to do in town, Frank.

57
00:03:13,059 --> 00:03:16,528
He can pick up his old job at Pop's
or help me down at the dress shop.

58
00:03:16,612 --> 00:03:17,531
Ah.

59
00:03:18,117 --> 00:03:21,837
You hear that?
You can work at your mom's dress shop.

60
00:03:21,921 --> 00:03:22,965
[FRANK CHUCKLES]

61
00:03:23,049 --> 00:03:25,389
I'll bet you wish
you didn't quit the team now.

62
00:03:29,402 --> 00:03:32,579
Let's motor, sis.
Train's leaving with or without you.

63
00:03:32,663 --> 00:03:34,460
[MILITARY BEAT PLAYING]

64
00:03:42,026 --> 00:03:44,575
And who, pray tell, was that?

65
00:03:44,659 --> 00:03:48,254
- You enlisting, Dad?
- Don't be asinine, the both of you.

66
00:03:48,337 --> 00:03:50,219
That was General Taylor from Washington.

67
00:03:50,303 --> 00:03:51,932
He was delivering unto me, uh...

68
00:03:52,978 --> 00:03:54,942
Well, a gift.

69
00:03:55,026 --> 00:03:56,322
Come into my study.

70
00:03:56,906 --> 00:03:58,161
I want you to see it.

71
00:03:58,244 --> 00:04:00,335
[MYSTERIOUS MUSIC PLAYING]

72
00:04:07,983 --> 00:04:10,868
What godforsaken creature is that?

73
00:04:10,951 --> 00:04:12,331
This is Moloch, Cheryl.

74
00:04:12,916 --> 00:04:14,420
An ancient pagan deity

75
00:04:14,505 --> 00:04:17,807
who can only be appeased
through child sacrifice.

76
00:04:19,269 --> 00:04:21,192
You should keep Moloch in mind,

77
00:04:21,275 --> 00:04:23,616
should you be inclined
to give me any more grief.

78
00:04:31,892 --> 00:04:33,314
[SCHOOL BELL RINGS]

79
00:04:33,858 --> 00:04:34,694
[JUGHEAD] Ethel.

80
00:04:37,076 --> 00:04:39,207
I don't mean to open old wounds,

81
00:04:39,292 --> 00:04:42,301
but that melting man
outside the Babylonium...

82
00:04:42,384 --> 00:04:43,345
What about him?

83
00:04:43,430 --> 00:04:46,690
You told Ben that he was wearing
the same uniform that your father did

84
00:04:46,773 --> 00:04:48,111
at the Blossom maple factory.

85
00:04:48,195 --> 00:04:51,078
I was just wondering
what your father did there.

86
00:04:51,162 --> 00:04:53,504
He was a janitor. Why?

87
00:04:53,587 --> 00:04:55,343
Did he ever get sick?

88
00:04:55,426 --> 00:04:57,725
My mom sometimes said
that he started drinking

89
00:04:57,808 --> 00:05:02,072
to help deal with the chronic pain
he felt in his stomach and his joints.

90
00:05:02,155 --> 00:05:04,539
And also because he was losing his hair.

91
00:05:05,416 --> 00:05:06,252
Golly.

92
00:05:06,796 --> 00:05:09,010
But why are you asking me about this?

93
00:05:12,271 --> 00:05:15,406
I can't say for certain,
but the fact that your father

94
00:05:15,489 --> 00:05:16,953
and the melting man,

95
00:05:17,036 --> 00:05:19,001
and Mr. Rayberry,
now that I think about it,

96
00:05:19,084 --> 00:05:20,923
all worked at the Blossom maple factory

97
00:05:21,007 --> 00:05:25,313
and all bit the linoleum in,
shall we say, bizarre circumstances...

98
00:05:26,567 --> 00:05:28,698
I don't think that's a coincidence.

99
00:05:28,781 --> 00:05:30,788
The Blossoms are hiding something,

100
00:05:30,872 --> 00:05:35,218
and I'm going to find out what,
so I can get us, you, me, Mrs. Rayberry...

101
00:05:35,929 --> 00:05:36,766
some closure.

102
00:05:38,062 --> 00:05:38,897
What?

103
00:05:40,444 --> 00:05:41,280
What is it?

104
00:05:41,782 --> 00:05:46,714
Jughead, I appreciate what you're doing,
but I'm trying to move on with my life.

105
00:05:47,675 --> 00:05:49,890
I'm applying for my driver's license.

106
00:05:49,974 --> 00:05:53,067
I got my car that I won
as Miss Riverdale Teen Queen.

107
00:05:53,903 --> 00:05:55,993
I'm going steady with Ben. Hi.

108
00:05:59,546 --> 00:06:02,263
You're going steady with our Ben?
Ben Button?

109
00:06:02,890 --> 00:06:06,861
In any case, I'm trying to put the past
where it belongs. Behind me.

110
00:06:06,945 --> 00:06:08,868
Class, finish taking your seats.

111
00:06:12,336 --> 00:06:14,134
Mayor Blossom and Principal Featherhead

112
00:06:14,217 --> 00:06:16,224
asked me to show you
this informational film

113
00:06:16,308 --> 00:06:19,986
about what to do in the event
of an atomic bomb detonating in Riverdale.

114
00:06:22,870 --> 00:06:26,298
[NARRATOR ON-SCREEN]
<i>Now we must be ready for a new danger,</i>

115
00:06:26,381 --> 00:06:27,552
<i>the atomic bomb.</i>

116
00:06:28,304 --> 00:06:31,439
<i>You will know when it comes.
There is a bright flash.</i>

117
00:06:31,523 --> 00:06:32,860
<i>Brighter than the sun.</i>

118
00:06:32,944 --> 00:06:36,831
<i>If you are not ready,
it could hurt you in different ways.</i>

119
00:06:36,915 --> 00:06:40,970
<i>It could knock you down hard
or throw you against a tree or a wall.</i>

120
00:06:41,471 --> 00:06:43,101
<i>It is such a big explosion</i>

121
00:06:43,185 --> 00:06:46,362
<i>it can smash in buildings
and knock signboards over</i>

122
00:06:46,445 --> 00:06:48,368
<i>and break windows all over town.</i>

123
00:06:48,451 --> 00:06:52,673
[ARCHIE] <i>Jeepers, that atomic-bomb movie
really gave me the zorros.</i>

124
00:06:52,756 --> 00:06:56,351
It should have. That dumb movie
was telling us to duck and cover,

125
00:06:56,436 --> 00:06:59,361
as if flying glass
is going to be the biggest of our worries.

126
00:06:59,445 --> 00:07:03,458
In truth, most of us wouldn't
likely survive an atomic explosion.

127
00:07:03,541 --> 00:07:05,589
What are you playing at, Jug?

128
00:07:05,673 --> 00:07:08,348
Have any of you seen
the newsreels from Japan?

129
00:07:09,059 --> 00:07:11,524
If a bomb drops on or near Riverdale,

130
00:07:11,609 --> 00:07:14,534
all of us are vaporized
in less than a nanosecond.

131
00:07:14,618 --> 00:07:16,959
Not to mention the radiation
we'd all be exposed to

132
00:07:17,042 --> 00:07:19,384
even if we manage to survive
the initial detonation.

133
00:07:19,467 --> 00:07:22,769
Well, I know what I'd do
if a bomb were heading our way.

134
00:07:22,852 --> 00:07:26,196
I'd sequester myself
in The Pembrooke's sub-sub-basement.

135
00:07:26,740 --> 00:07:29,541
It's like a little underground city
down there.

136
00:07:29,624 --> 00:07:31,588
You'd be invited, Juggykins.

137
00:07:31,672 --> 00:07:32,591
[GROANS]

138
00:07:33,721 --> 00:07:36,396
I would seek shelter
in the abandoned Blossom mines.

139
00:07:36,479 --> 00:07:39,363
They've stood strong
since before the Revolutionary War.

140
00:07:39,447 --> 00:07:42,164
Isn't it dark and cold
down in those mines?

141
00:07:42,247 --> 00:07:45,132
Hmm. Why, yes, Tony, it is.

142
00:07:45,842 --> 00:07:48,852
I would have to find some way
to stay cozy and warm.

143
00:07:50,190 --> 00:07:51,569
[REGGIE] I'd head to Duck Creek.

144
00:07:51,652 --> 00:07:54,453
We've got a well so deep
no bomb or radiation could reach it.

145
00:07:54,536 --> 00:07:56,250
Well, why stop at Duck Creek?

146
00:07:56,919 --> 00:07:59,218
If we hear these sirens,
I'm hopping in my hot rod,

147
00:07:59,302 --> 00:08:01,308
I'm grabbing my mom,
and I'm heading out West.

148
00:08:01,976 --> 00:08:05,070
There's no way these radiation clouds
are going to cross the Rockies.

149
00:08:05,696 --> 00:08:07,034
Out West sounds nice.

150
00:08:07,745 --> 00:08:08,665
Sure does.

151
00:08:08,748 --> 00:08:11,465
You can't outrun an atomic bomb, Archie.

152
00:08:11,549 --> 00:08:13,639
No matter how fast your hot rod is.

153
00:08:13,722 --> 00:08:18,237
Guys, I read somewhere
that if you are inside of a refrigerator

154
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:20,619
when the big one hits, you're safe.

155
00:08:20,703 --> 00:08:22,458
But then you're inside a refrigerator.

156
00:08:22,542 --> 00:08:25,301
Yeah. What would you do
about food and water?

157
00:08:26,304 --> 00:08:27,851
I'd be in a refrigerator.

158
00:08:27,934 --> 00:08:29,147
[ALL CHUCKLE]

159
00:08:29,230 --> 00:08:30,860
I'm not holing up anywhere.

160
00:08:30,944 --> 00:08:33,870
Come on, guys,
we can't let this bomb get us down.

161
00:08:34,789 --> 00:08:37,506
In Nevada, where the U.S.
does most of its atomic testing,

162
00:08:37,590 --> 00:08:40,056
people have bomb shelters
in case something goes wrong.

163
00:08:40,140 --> 00:08:41,937
That's what it'd take to be truly safe.

164
00:08:42,856 --> 00:08:44,780
A lead-lined underground bunker.

165
00:08:44,863 --> 00:08:46,911
[BETTY] If Russia wanted to bomb us,

166
00:08:46,994 --> 00:08:51,467
{\an8}wouldn't they target larger cities
like Los Angeles or New York?

167
00:08:51,550 --> 00:08:53,348
{\an8}People who live in the sticks, like us,

168
00:08:53,432 --> 00:08:58,281
{\an8}we don't actually have to worry
about nuclear attacks, do we?

169
00:08:58,364 --> 00:09:00,663
{\an8}Mm. I wouldn't bet the farm on it.

170
00:09:01,499 --> 00:09:05,637
An atomic bomb could drop anywhere,
even here in Riverdale.

171
00:09:05,721 --> 00:09:08,271
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

172
00:09:13,872 --> 00:09:16,840
{\an8}It says,
"Make rope and wrap around the rope."

173
00:09:17,508 --> 00:09:18,428
Whatever that means.

174
00:09:19,181 --> 00:09:20,727
{\an8}[ARCHIE] Say, what are you fellas up to?

175
00:09:20,810 --> 00:09:24,112
Trying to tie a sailor's knot
and failing miserably.

176
00:09:24,197 --> 00:09:26,328
{\an8}A sailor's knot? I can show you how.

177
00:09:26,914 --> 00:09:29,170
{\an8}Don't you remember
your Adventure Scouts training?

178
00:09:30,549 --> 00:09:34,019
{\an8}The rabbit goes out the hole,
around the tree,

179
00:09:35,858 --> 00:09:39,119
{\an8}back through the hole again.
You should get a nice loop.

180
00:09:40,080 --> 00:09:42,129
What are you practicing this for?

181
00:09:42,212 --> 00:09:43,842
{\an8}You do realize, if the bomb hits,

182
00:09:43,926 --> 00:09:46,099
{\an8}there's not much
a sailor's knot can do for you.

183
00:09:47,813 --> 00:09:50,823
{\an8}Kevin and I are considering
joining the Merchant Marines.

184
00:09:51,408 --> 00:09:52,411
{\an8}Merchant Marines?

185
00:09:52,494 --> 00:09:55,504
{\an8}Wow, what is that,
part of the Navy or something?

186
00:09:55,588 --> 00:09:57,009
{\an8}No, it's a civilian job.

187
00:09:57,092 --> 00:10:00,437
{\an8}They pay you to work on a cargo ship
and travel around the world.

188
00:10:01,523 --> 00:10:05,495
{\an8}Archie, you might be keen on this. A lot
of great writers were Merchant Marines.

189
00:10:05,578 --> 00:10:07,124
A lot of beats served too.

190
00:10:07,208 --> 00:10:10,426
{\an8}Ginsberg and Kerouac
both did time on the Seven Seas.

191
00:10:11,304 --> 00:10:13,729
{\an8}"Adventure awaits you on the open water."

192
00:10:15,192 --> 00:10:17,824
{\an8}I wouldn't hate
getting away from my uncle.

193
00:10:17,909 --> 00:10:21,461
{\an8}And seeing the world, having adventures?
That would enrich my writing.

194
00:10:21,546 --> 00:10:23,343
{\an8}That sounds super swell to me.

195
00:10:24,806 --> 00:10:27,731
{\an8}- And I do love tying knots.
- There's a recruiter coming tomorrow.

196
00:10:27,815 --> 00:10:30,950
{\an8}You can ask him questions
and hear what he has to say.

197
00:10:31,786 --> 00:10:35,590
{\an8}Ladies, you are the drivers of tomorrow.

198
00:10:36,760 --> 00:10:39,184
{\an8}As such, it is important to learn

199
00:10:39,268 --> 00:10:45,455
{\an8}to be alert, confident,
conscientious motor-vehicle operators.

200
00:10:45,538 --> 00:10:48,339
- Stop sign.
- [STUDENT GASPS]

201
00:10:48,422 --> 00:10:52,435
{\an8}Driving is not a right,
as many young men believe.

202
00:10:53,062 --> 00:10:55,988
{\an8}It is a privilege and a responsibility.

203
00:10:56,531 --> 00:10:58,329
{\an8}Upcoming left turn.

204
00:11:00,586 --> 00:11:03,721
{\an8}That's wonderful.
Let's bring our cars into "park."

205
00:11:05,226 --> 00:11:06,437
And shake it out.

206
00:11:06,522 --> 00:11:08,403
Very good. Excellent.

207
00:11:08,486 --> 00:11:12,206
{\an8}Now, your homework for tonight is to rest.

208
00:11:12,289 --> 00:11:15,676
{\an8}Because tomorrow
your true test of skills begins.

209
00:11:16,554 --> 00:11:20,064
{\an8}We will be getting
into a real working automobile...

210
00:11:21,485 --> 00:11:23,534
to practice parallel parking.

211
00:11:23,617 --> 00:11:25,290
[STUDENTS MURMURING]

212
00:11:25,833 --> 00:11:26,961
[GIRL] That's too bad.

213
00:11:27,589 --> 00:11:30,514
{\an8}How was school today?
Anything interesting happen?

214
00:11:30,598 --> 00:11:31,434
{\an8}We watched a movie

215
00:11:31,517 --> 00:11:34,401
{\an8}that taught us what to do
if the Russians drop a bomb on us.

216
00:11:35,279 --> 00:11:37,203
{\an8}I'm thinking of joining
the Merchant Marines.

217
00:11:37,286 --> 00:11:40,003
{\an8}Well, as long as
you finish high school first.

218
00:11:40,086 --> 00:11:42,887
{\an8}When that day comes,
I hope you'll still consider college.

219
00:11:43,890 --> 00:11:45,228
Wait a minute, Mary.

220
00:11:45,311 --> 00:11:48,363
{\an8}Merchant Marines sounds
like a solid, sensible idea.

221
00:11:48,864 --> 00:11:52,208
{\an8}Much better than going to some college
to pursue poetry.

222
00:11:54,633 --> 00:11:58,520
{\an8}The Merchant Marines would be a way
for me to pursue my poetry.

223
00:11:58,603 --> 00:12:01,947
{\an8}A lot of beats would join to learn more
about themselves or the world,

224
00:12:02,031 --> 00:12:03,076
{\an8}then to write about it.

225
00:12:03,703 --> 00:12:05,876
{\an8}You'd know that
if you ever cracked open a book.

226
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:08,802
- What was that?
- No one is joining anything tonight.

227
00:12:08,886 --> 00:12:11,895
So can we please
just finish our supper in peace?

228
00:12:13,526 --> 00:12:15,699
[JUGHEAD] <i>Well, Dilton,
what's the occasion?</i>

229
00:12:15,783 --> 00:12:16,619
[DILTON] I...

230
00:12:17,789 --> 00:12:19,294
I just came by because...

231
00:12:20,297 --> 00:12:23,014
after the melting man
and that movie my dad showed in class,

232
00:12:23,098 --> 00:12:24,937
I know you're unsettled.

233
00:12:25,021 --> 00:12:27,905
Sue me.
I don't want to die in an atomic attack.

234
00:12:27,988 --> 00:12:28,824
Yeah.

235
00:12:28,908 --> 00:12:32,085
Except you don't have to worry, Jughead.

236
00:12:32,168 --> 00:12:35,136
You're one of my best pals,
my comic-book buddy.

237
00:12:35,220 --> 00:12:40,361
If anything bad were to actually happen,
I'd take care of you. You'd be safe.

238
00:12:40,444 --> 00:12:45,127
Well, that's swell of you to say, Dilton.
But how would I be safe?

239
00:12:46,631 --> 00:12:50,686
It's... It would probably be easier
if I just showed you.

240
00:12:50,769 --> 00:12:52,775
[METAL GROANING]

241
00:12:55,451 --> 00:12:58,794
Holy crap-ola, Dilton.

242
00:13:00,885 --> 00:13:03,309
How does your family have a bunker?

243
00:13:03,810 --> 00:13:05,106
My dad built it.

244
00:13:05,190 --> 00:13:08,033
He says we're deep enough
to survive an atomic blast.

245
00:13:08,116 --> 00:13:10,247
And any radiation after the blast.

246
00:13:10,958 --> 00:13:12,505
Am I missing something?

247
00:13:13,466 --> 00:13:15,891
Does your dad think
that Riverdale could be a target?

248
00:13:19,485 --> 00:13:20,363
Dilton?

249
00:13:21,408 --> 00:13:23,248
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

250
00:13:23,331 --> 00:13:25,170
What does your dad know that we don't?

251
00:13:26,633 --> 00:13:27,929
Nothing for certain.

252
00:13:29,141 --> 00:13:32,067
But about a year
before Ethel's folks were killed,

253
00:13:32,903 --> 00:13:34,742
her dad showed up to our house.

254
00:13:36,330 --> 00:13:37,751
With this.

255
00:13:41,598 --> 00:13:44,147
Mr. Muggs wanted to see
if it was worth anything.

256
00:13:44,816 --> 00:13:47,742
He figured since my dad
was a science teacher, he'd know.

257
00:13:48,913 --> 00:13:50,960
- What is it?
- Palladium.

258
00:13:52,591 --> 00:13:55,057
Mr. Muggs said he swiped it from work.

259
00:13:55,768 --> 00:13:58,275
- The maple factory?
- I guess so.

260
00:13:58,359 --> 00:14:01,452
He said Clifford Blossom
was sitting on a pile of it,

261
00:14:01,535 --> 00:14:03,458
and doing something with it.

262
00:14:04,712 --> 00:14:06,886
That's when my dad
started building this bunker.

263
00:14:08,182 --> 00:14:12,780
Because Clifford Blossom was
or is doing something with palladium?

264
00:14:14,118 --> 00:14:15,246
A secret something?

265
00:14:16,124 --> 00:14:17,210
Worth killing for?

266
00:14:17,294 --> 00:14:20,847
In its inert state,
palladium is basically harmless.

267
00:14:21,558 --> 00:14:25,654
But in its purest state,
concentrated and compressed,

268
00:14:26,574 --> 00:14:30,628
some scientists speculate
it could be more volatile than plutonium

269
00:14:30,712 --> 00:14:35,853
and, if detonated,
more destructive than a hydrogen bomb.

270
00:14:38,445 --> 00:14:40,241
This is starting to ring a bell for me.

271
00:14:40,326 --> 00:14:43,210
[JUGHEAD] <i>Not just a bell, in fact,
a four-alarm siren.</i>

272
00:14:43,293 --> 00:14:45,467
<i>I'd recently had my nose in a story</i>

273
00:14:45,550 --> 00:14:47,849
<i>about a palladium bomb
destroying a small town</i>

274
00:14:47,933 --> 00:14:50,650
<i>by my former deceased mentor,
Brad Rayberry,</i>

275
00:14:50,733 --> 00:14:53,534
<i>who, at one point,
worked at the Blossom factory.</i>

276
00:14:53,618 --> 00:14:55,917
<i>Had he seen or heard something there
about palladium</i>

277
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:57,672
<i>that had inspired his story?</i>

278
00:14:57,756 --> 00:15:00,055
[SIREN WAILING]

279
00:15:00,139 --> 00:15:03,022
That's the emergency siren!
As we were warned!

280
00:15:03,106 --> 00:15:05,865
This is it! This is the big one!

281
00:15:05,949 --> 00:15:07,788
[STUDENTS SCREAMING]

282
00:15:13,013 --> 00:15:17,193
Jughead, duck and cover!
Jughead! Jughead, what are you doing?

283
00:15:17,276 --> 00:15:21,957
Get under your desk! No!
Jughead! Get away from the...

284
00:15:22,042 --> 00:15:24,048
[SCREAMING]

285
00:15:31,279 --> 00:15:32,366
[GASPS]

286
00:15:37,005 --> 00:15:39,722
Damn you and your fearmongering,
Jughead Jones.

287
00:15:47,455 --> 00:15:49,169
[CLIFFORD IN RUSSIAN]
Everything is in readiness.

288
00:15:49,253 --> 00:15:51,259
Project Moloch is almost complete.

289
00:15:51,510 --> 00:15:53,474
[PENELOPE IN RUSSIAN]
It's unfortunate what happened to that man

290
00:15:53,558 --> 00:15:55,147
who escaped from the infirmary.

291
00:15:55,314 --> 00:15:59,577
[CLIFFORD] Yes, but we knew
there might be casualties. Sacrifices.

292
00:15:59,661 --> 00:16:04,091
And his family will be taken care of...

293
00:16:04,175 --> 00:16:09,359
[PENELOPE] Think of how it will be
when we return to the Motherland.

294
00:16:09,442 --> 00:16:12,242
Triumphant. As heroes.

295
00:16:12,577 --> 00:16:14,541
Our leaders will be pleased.

296
00:16:14,625 --> 00:16:18,889
They promised me an appointment
in your government, don't forget...

297
00:16:20,142 --> 00:16:21,981
[FLOOR CREAKS]

298
00:16:22,065 --> 00:16:23,069
[GASPS]

299
00:16:23,152 --> 00:16:25,869
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

300
00:16:30,341 --> 00:16:32,557
As a Merchant Marine,
you'll travel the globe

301
00:16:32,641 --> 00:16:35,400
on the world's
most technologically advanced ships.

302
00:16:35,483 --> 00:16:39,120
You'll work and train alongside this
country's best and brightest young men,

303
00:16:39,203 --> 00:16:41,334
all eager to experience life
to the fullest.

304
00:16:42,547 --> 00:16:43,383
Yes, son?

305
00:16:44,051 --> 00:16:46,477
Would we have time
to explore places we'd be visiting?

306
00:16:46,560 --> 00:16:48,231
Really get to soak them up?

307
00:16:48,316 --> 00:16:49,987
This isn't a pleasure cruise.

308
00:16:50,070 --> 00:16:53,665
Something you should all know,
no one is guaranteed a spot.

309
00:16:56,842 --> 00:16:59,058
Cheryl. Hi-ho.

310
00:17:01,398 --> 00:17:03,656
Has anything strange
been happening at your house?

311
00:17:03,739 --> 00:17:06,540
Mayhaps. Why do you care?

312
00:17:06,624 --> 00:17:08,965
I heard you mention those abandoned mines.

313
00:17:09,048 --> 00:17:11,640
I wonder if they're close
to your family's maple factory.

314
00:17:11,723 --> 00:17:14,816
The factory is practically
right on top of them, yes.

315
00:17:14,900 --> 00:17:18,704
Okay. Look, Cheryl,
this is going to sound like gobbledygook,

316
00:17:19,582 --> 00:17:21,546
but I believe
your father is up to no good.

317
00:17:21,629 --> 00:17:24,305
I think he is involved
in the Milkman murders,

318
00:17:24,388 --> 00:17:25,767
not to mention the melting man.

319
00:17:25,851 --> 00:17:29,487
And I think that those mines
are actually palladium mines

320
00:17:29,572 --> 00:17:31,160
and they're not abandoned.

321
00:17:31,243 --> 00:17:33,877
There's no love lost
between my father and I.

322
00:17:33,960 --> 00:17:35,967
I'm certain if he had the chance,

323
00:17:36,051 --> 00:17:38,558
he would sacrifice me
to a pagan god named Moloch.

324
00:17:38,642 --> 00:17:41,275
But to your point, he has been meeting

325
00:17:41,359 --> 00:17:43,867
with an Army general
in his study recently,

326
00:17:44,369 --> 00:17:47,211
and I did overhear him
and my mother last night

327
00:17:47,294 --> 00:17:49,593
speaking what I believe was Russian.

328
00:17:49,677 --> 00:17:55,278
Holy moly. Do you think
you can get in there and play gumshoe?

329
00:17:55,362 --> 00:17:58,037
Just poke around, snoop,
see if you find anything incriminating?

330
00:17:58,121 --> 00:17:59,542
[ENGINE STARTS]

331
00:18:00,085 --> 00:18:02,091
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

332
00:18:08,946 --> 00:18:09,782
[TIRES SCREECH]

333
00:18:20,525 --> 00:18:22,866
[STUDENTS CHEERING]

334
00:18:25,040 --> 00:18:26,126
[GIRL] Great job!

335
00:18:26,711 --> 00:18:31,101
I'm very pleased to announce that
since all of you passed both the written

336
00:18:31,184 --> 00:18:34,402
and practical portions
of your driver's education exam,

337
00:18:34,486 --> 00:18:39,042
we'll all be taking a field trip to
the Riverdale Department of Motor Vehicles

338
00:18:39,126 --> 00:18:40,505
at the end of the week.

339
00:18:41,968 --> 00:18:44,518
But, girls, this is very important.

340
00:18:45,271 --> 00:18:49,869
To obtain your legal license, you must
bring a copy of your birth certificate.

341
00:18:50,662 --> 00:18:54,007
The DMV needs to make sure
none of you are Russian spies.

342
00:18:54,090 --> 00:18:55,846
[STUDENTS CHUCKLE]

343
00:19:04,540 --> 00:19:06,546
I was wondering why the light was on.

344
00:19:07,717 --> 00:19:10,851
Let me guess.
This is for the Merchant Marines.

345
00:19:11,562 --> 00:19:14,404
The recruiter said
everyone rows at least an hour a day

346
00:19:14,488 --> 00:19:16,870
when they're out at sea to stay in shape.

347
00:19:16,955 --> 00:19:19,587
So I'm just getting a head start.

348
00:19:21,176 --> 00:19:22,346
Listen, about that.

349
00:19:23,182 --> 00:19:25,774
Can we talk man to man for a minute?

350
00:19:28,826 --> 00:19:30,455
I know I'm not your father,

351
00:19:31,500 --> 00:19:32,754
but just so you know,

352
00:19:33,799 --> 00:19:36,433
I want what's best for you,
just as he would.

353
00:19:42,160 --> 00:19:43,288
What is that?

354
00:19:44,333 --> 00:19:47,509
Your old man's dog tags.
He'd want you to have them.

355
00:19:47,593 --> 00:19:51,063
Like he'd want you
to quit this Merchant Marines business.

356
00:19:51,982 --> 00:19:55,535
Join the Army. Enlist. Just like he did.

357
00:19:58,085 --> 00:19:59,046
You didn't know?

358
00:20:01,345 --> 00:20:04,689
Your father wasn't drafted.
He volunteered for the Army.

359
00:20:05,483 --> 00:20:08,953
He knew what being a real man
and a good American meant.

360
00:20:09,914 --> 00:20:13,007
He believed there was no greater duty
than serving this country

361
00:20:13,091 --> 00:20:15,432
and fighting for democracy and freedom.

362
00:20:16,309 --> 00:20:18,190
You wanna be like your father, don't you?

363
00:20:18,274 --> 00:20:20,281
[EMOTIONAL MUSIC PLAYING]

364
00:20:21,117 --> 00:20:24,251
Yeah. I try to be like him every day.

365
00:20:24,335 --> 00:20:27,554
Well, then drop this poetry nonsense
and join the Army.

366
00:20:27,637 --> 00:20:30,020
Become the kind of man he'd be proud of.

367
00:20:30,103 --> 00:20:33,823
The man I know is inside you,
fighting to get out.

368
00:20:35,872 --> 00:20:41,431
And the best part about joining the Army?
You don't have to wait until graduation.

369
00:20:54,807 --> 00:20:56,813
[FOREBODING MUSIC PLAYING]

370
00:21:08,224 --> 00:21:10,398
Let's see what you're hiding, Daddy.

371
00:21:47,265 --> 00:21:48,519
A draft?

372
00:22:25,679 --> 00:22:27,225
[PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING]

373
00:22:40,768 --> 00:22:43,318
Good morning, honey. One waffle or two?

374
00:22:44,112 --> 00:22:44,948
Uh...

375
00:22:46,161 --> 00:22:47,874
Are those your dad's...?

376
00:22:47,958 --> 00:22:49,839
Dog tags? Yeah.

377
00:22:50,967 --> 00:22:54,604
- Uncle Frank gave them to me.
- Why would he have done that?

378
00:22:57,154 --> 00:23:02,127
Well, I think I know, but maybe you
should sit down so we can talk about it.

379
00:23:11,281 --> 00:23:13,748
Betty, can we talk for a second?

380
00:23:13,832 --> 00:23:14,751
Sure.

381
00:23:16,465 --> 00:23:18,095
Are things not hunky dory?

382
00:23:18,764 --> 00:23:20,812
No, there's a problem.

383
00:23:20,895 --> 00:23:24,072
Um, I don't have my birth certificate.

384
00:23:24,783 --> 00:23:25,786
It's at my house.

385
00:23:27,542 --> 00:23:30,844
- Where my parents...
- Don't worry. I'll grab it for you.

386
00:23:31,597 --> 00:23:33,686
- Really, Betty?
- Sure. Yeah.

387
00:23:33,770 --> 00:23:36,361
I'll book it there
before we go to the DMV.

388
00:23:36,445 --> 00:23:39,705
You have any idea
where your birth certificate would be?

389
00:23:39,790 --> 00:23:43,258
My mom had a crafting desk
where she kept important papers.

390
00:23:43,928 --> 00:23:45,432
I bet you it's in there.

391
00:23:46,100 --> 00:23:47,773
[SCHOOL BELL RINGS]

392
00:23:56,969 --> 00:23:59,268
- Did you find something?
- Did I ever.

393
00:23:59,351 --> 00:24:01,316
- You were right.
- About what part?

394
00:24:01,400 --> 00:24:04,032
Everything.
Snooping through Daddy's study,

395
00:24:04,117 --> 00:24:07,544
I stumbled upon a secret panel
and found a bunch of these.

396
00:24:07,627 --> 00:24:09,634
[INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING]

397
00:24:11,014 --> 00:24:14,817
- And matching uniforms to boot.
- Holy Toledo.

398
00:24:16,740 --> 00:24:19,875
The Milkman must have been
working for your father,

399
00:24:19,958 --> 00:24:21,547
doing his bidding.

400
00:24:22,550 --> 00:24:24,891
- Are you in danger?
- No more than usual.

401
00:24:25,559 --> 00:24:28,151
I also went to the mines.
You were right about those too.

402
00:24:28,234 --> 00:24:29,739
They are palladium mines.

403
00:24:30,701 --> 00:24:32,164
Very much not abandoned.

404
00:24:33,669 --> 00:24:36,679
Meet me on the Thornhill grounds tonight
and bring your camera,

405
00:24:36,762 --> 00:24:39,562
and pray an atomic disaster
doesn't befall us all before then.

406
00:25:40,172 --> 00:25:41,091
What...? What...?

407
00:25:46,400 --> 00:25:48,656
What was my dad paying the Muggses for?

408
00:26:02,953 --> 00:26:07,466
So, Frank, Archie told me about
your little talk in the garage last night.

409
00:26:09,180 --> 00:26:10,476
[FRANK] Did he, now?

410
00:26:11,061 --> 00:26:12,107
What did he say?

411
00:26:12,190 --> 00:26:15,785
A few things, but it sounded to me
like you used his father,

412
00:26:15,868 --> 00:26:19,797
your brother, to try to manipulate my son
into joining the Army.

413
00:26:20,675 --> 00:26:24,061
How dare you?
Especially when you yourself never served.

414
00:26:26,360 --> 00:26:30,289
The Army is the best place for him, Mary.
It'll set him straight.

415
00:26:30,372 --> 00:26:33,967
Let's not mince words.
We all know what this is really about.

416
00:26:34,051 --> 00:26:36,809
It's you not wanting Archie
to write poetry.

417
00:26:36,894 --> 00:26:39,360
He's on the road to ruin. He's...

418
00:26:40,655 --> 00:26:43,038
- Well, he's lost.
- [MARY] He's not lost.

419
00:26:43,121 --> 00:26:45,922
He's 17.
He's got his whole life ahead of him.

420
00:26:46,006 --> 00:26:49,308
Whether that's joining
the Merchant Marines or the Army

421
00:26:49,392 --> 00:26:54,115
or going to college to study literature
and poetry after he finishes high school.

422
00:26:54,699 --> 00:26:58,587
But he'll be the one who decides his path,
not his bullying uncle.

423
00:26:59,214 --> 00:27:00,301
[MARY SIGHS]

424
00:27:00,385 --> 00:27:04,063
I can't have you here anymore.
It's time for you to move out.

425
00:27:05,693 --> 00:27:09,706
- You called me here to help.
- Now she's telling you to hit the road.

426
00:27:09,789 --> 00:27:12,046
Who's gonna be the man of the house?

427
00:27:12,130 --> 00:27:15,475
- I am.
- Not that I need one.

428
00:27:15,558 --> 00:27:17,940
I am the woman of this house, after all.

429
00:27:18,024 --> 00:27:20,031
I'm the one who pays the mortgage.

430
00:27:21,242 --> 00:27:23,751
I suppose I could shack up
with Tom Keller.

431
00:27:24,879 --> 00:27:28,014
I hear he's been handed
marching orders recently.

432
00:27:28,097 --> 00:27:30,438
Wonderful. That works out for everyone.

433
00:27:41,558 --> 00:27:43,564
Betty. How you doing, kiddo?

434
00:27:43,647 --> 00:27:46,740
Why were you two
writing checks once a month,

435
00:27:47,450 --> 00:27:49,541
year after year, to the Muggses?

436
00:27:49,624 --> 00:27:51,631
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

437
00:27:53,554 --> 00:27:57,775
Because, Betty,
Mrs. Muggs was our housekeeper.

438
00:27:57,859 --> 00:28:01,537
Those must have been payments for,
you know, services.

439
00:28:01,621 --> 00:28:03,501
That doesn't make any sense.

440
00:28:03,586 --> 00:28:05,675
Some checks are from two years ago.

441
00:28:05,759 --> 00:28:08,225
If Mrs. Muggs were ever our housekeeper,

442
00:28:08,309 --> 00:28:10,650
she hadn't been
for as long as I can remember.

443
00:28:12,029 --> 00:28:14,704
Oh, and what's the story
behind this photo?

444
00:28:16,710 --> 00:28:17,755
Who's that baby?

445
00:28:18,508 --> 00:28:20,890
Because it's not me. And it's not Polly.

446
00:28:21,601 --> 00:28:22,771
That's Ethel.

447
00:28:23,607 --> 00:28:28,958
Why did the Muggses have a photo
of you holding Ethel as a baby?

448
00:28:30,421 --> 00:28:35,060
Because the Muggses asked
if I would be Ethel's godfather,

449
00:28:35,813 --> 00:28:37,067
and I agreed.

450
00:28:37,151 --> 00:28:40,369
So why I haven't heard about this?
Why hasn't anyone?

451
00:28:40,453 --> 00:28:41,456
[SPLUTTERS]

452
00:28:41,539 --> 00:28:43,880
- I don't know. I...
- [ALICE] Stop, Hal.

453
00:28:45,762 --> 00:28:47,057
Just stop.

454
00:28:48,771 --> 00:28:51,947
It's over. Can't you see that?

455
00:28:55,919 --> 00:28:58,719
You're Ethel's father, aren't you?

456
00:29:00,182 --> 00:29:02,397
Why don't you go for a walk, dear? Hmm?

457
00:29:04,069 --> 00:29:06,744
So that Betty and I
can have a little chat.

458
00:29:13,892 --> 00:29:18,992
Mildred Muggs did clean our house
before you were born. That part is true.

459
00:29:20,580 --> 00:29:24,509
And at some point, she and your father
started having an affair.

460
00:29:25,554 --> 00:29:27,936
And I suspected it for a long time,

461
00:29:28,021 --> 00:29:29,692
but it was confirmed when...

462
00:29:29,775 --> 00:29:31,323
Mrs. Muggs got pregnant.

463
00:29:31,991 --> 00:29:34,834
Your father admitted everything.

464
00:29:34,918 --> 00:29:39,389
He was crying, apologizing.
He didn't know what to do.

465
00:29:39,474 --> 00:29:42,984
I mean, if any whiff
of the scandal got out,

466
00:29:43,779 --> 00:29:46,789
the consequences for the station,

467
00:29:46,872 --> 00:29:49,798
for us, for our family...

468
00:29:50,467 --> 00:29:51,679
So you stayed with him.

469
00:29:51,762 --> 00:29:53,393
I had no other choice.

470
00:29:53,936 --> 00:29:56,946
Yes, I stayed, but I handled it.

471
00:29:57,991 --> 00:29:59,495
I made a deal with the Muggses

472
00:29:59,578 --> 00:30:03,591
that if they raise the baby as their own
and keep our secret,

473
00:30:03,675 --> 00:30:08,649
that we would financially support
the child until she turned 16.

474
00:30:08,733 --> 00:30:09,694
Support...

475
00:30:11,241 --> 00:30:13,457
Ethel, my sister.

476
00:30:13,540 --> 00:30:14,543
Your half sister.

477
00:30:16,466 --> 00:30:20,437
This is why you adopted Ethel.

478
00:30:20,520 --> 00:30:22,986
[EMOTIONAL MUSIC PLAYING]

479
00:30:23,071 --> 00:30:28,253
This is why you've been the way
that you've been with me...

480
00:30:31,054 --> 00:30:33,269
wanting Kevin to pin me over Archie.

481
00:30:35,443 --> 00:30:38,202
Why you were scared of me
reading Dr. Kingsley's book.

482
00:30:40,417 --> 00:30:44,639
You were afraid of something
like what happened to you happening to me.

483
00:30:46,018 --> 00:30:52,121
I just wanted
to give you a good, happy life.

484
00:30:52,204 --> 00:30:53,625
Unburdened.

485
00:30:54,462 --> 00:30:56,342
Safe, free of shame.

486
00:30:57,345 --> 00:31:02,738
You've been obsessed
with presenting as the perfect family,

487
00:31:02,821 --> 00:31:04,117
when all along...

488
00:31:06,918 --> 00:31:09,050
this is what's been wrong, this...

489
00:31:11,265 --> 00:31:14,107
secret, this shame.

490
00:31:14,191 --> 00:31:16,197
Not what I've been doing.

491
00:31:17,326 --> 00:31:18,622
Or what Polly did.

492
00:31:21,129 --> 00:31:22,467
It was Dad's affair...

493
00:31:25,101 --> 00:31:29,615
and your decision to stay with him
and pretend that everything was fine.

494
00:31:30,451 --> 00:31:32,206
And for all my efforts...

495
00:31:34,004 --> 00:31:35,551
I failed you.

496
00:31:36,344 --> 00:31:38,602
[ALICE WEEPING]

497
00:31:38,685 --> 00:31:43,701
As a mother, I failed you, and I'm sorry.

498
00:31:48,675 --> 00:31:49,678
You didn't.

499
00:31:52,437 --> 00:31:54,361
You did the best that you could.

500
00:31:57,411 --> 00:31:59,752
You did what you thought was right.

501
00:32:02,929 --> 00:32:03,765
But now...

502
00:32:06,775 --> 00:32:08,614
we need to get Dad back here...

503
00:32:10,370 --> 00:32:13,797
and we need to tell Ethel everything.

504
00:32:23,619 --> 00:32:25,626
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

505
00:32:35,365 --> 00:32:37,957
[TV ANNOUNCER] Oh, Mija!
<i>Starring Hiram Lodge...</i>

506
00:32:50,873 --> 00:32:53,549
If what you say is here is really here...

507
00:32:53,632 --> 00:32:55,596
It is. You will see for yourself.

508
00:32:55,680 --> 00:32:57,059
Wouldn't there be more guards?

509
00:32:57,142 --> 00:33:00,612
I imagine my father
is trying to avoid undue attention.

510
00:33:00,696 --> 00:33:01,908
That's a good point.

511
00:33:02,661 --> 00:33:04,457
[JUGHEAD] <i>And as Cheryl and I
were on the cusp</i>

512
00:33:04,542 --> 00:33:05,963
<i>of uncovering one explosive truth,</i>

513
00:33:06,046 --> 00:33:08,596
<i>Ethel was experiencing
emotional shock waves</i>

514
00:33:08,680 --> 00:33:11,062
<i>after learning the truth about her life.</i>

515
00:33:11,146 --> 00:33:12,317
It explains things.

516
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:14,364
[EMOTIONAL MUSIC PLAYING]

517
00:33:14,448 --> 00:33:18,419
Why my parents were so sad,
why they fought all the time...

518
00:33:21,053 --> 00:33:22,348
why I always felt...

519
00:33:24,103 --> 00:33:25,817
like it was somehow my fault.

520
00:33:26,570 --> 00:33:28,953
Oh. It was never your fault, Ethel.

521
00:33:30,122 --> 00:33:31,000
Ethel...

522
00:33:33,007 --> 00:33:35,683
Mrs. Cooper and I were discussing, and...

523
00:33:37,689 --> 00:33:39,193
well, we'd like to...

524
00:33:39,276 --> 00:33:43,499
We'd like to make things right
and formally adopt you,

525
00:33:44,711 --> 00:33:47,428
show you that we could be a true family.

526
00:33:52,737 --> 00:33:56,373
I appreciate that, Mr. and Mrs. Cooper.

527
00:33:57,293 --> 00:33:58,839
It's kind of you to offer.

528
00:34:01,221 --> 00:34:03,186
I don't think that's what I want.

529
00:34:04,983 --> 00:34:06,112
What do you want?

530
00:34:07,617 --> 00:34:08,495
To be happy.

531
00:34:11,713 --> 00:34:13,134
To move on with my life.

532
00:34:15,308 --> 00:34:16,186
To start over.

533
00:34:23,835 --> 00:34:27,179
You enjoy my room
and don't get into too much trouble.

534
00:34:27,263 --> 00:34:30,606
I won't.
And I'll see you at practice, coach.

535
00:34:33,908 --> 00:34:38,423
Mary. I don't know how I'm gonna survive
without your chicken pot pie.

536
00:34:38,506 --> 00:34:39,970
Oh, come on, Frank.

537
00:34:40,053 --> 00:34:42,854
You know you'll always be welcome
at Sunday dinner.

538
00:34:45,069 --> 00:34:46,365
[EMOTIONAL MUSIC PLAYING]

539
00:34:46,449 --> 00:34:48,915
Well, in that case, I will see you Sunday.

540
00:34:51,088 --> 00:34:55,811
You. So you're the man of the house now.
I hope you're up for the task.

541
00:34:55,895 --> 00:34:59,741
And, uh... I hope
you don't hold anything against me.

542
00:35:01,747 --> 00:35:03,378
Of course not, Uncle Frank.

543
00:35:04,882 --> 00:35:09,229
But just to be clear, writing poetry
doesn't make you any less of a man.

544
00:35:10,191 --> 00:35:13,869
Some of the most beautiful poems
were written by soldiers in trenches

545
00:35:13,953 --> 00:35:16,084
covered in mud
and the blood of their brothers.

546
00:35:17,422 --> 00:35:19,177
Well, maybe that's my path.

547
00:35:21,936 --> 00:35:25,280
Well, maybe not.
I guess we'll have to wait and see.

548
00:35:26,367 --> 00:35:27,579
Mm-hm.

549
00:35:43,839 --> 00:35:46,263
We have to show these photos
to Sheriff Keller.

550
00:35:46,347 --> 00:35:47,183
Maybe.

551
00:35:47,852 --> 00:35:50,778
Maybe not. For all we know,
Sheriff Keller is in on it.

552
00:35:50,861 --> 00:35:52,659
Kevin's father? No.

553
00:35:52,742 --> 00:35:55,669
He's just a dimwitted small-town sheriff
that's in over his head.

554
00:35:55,752 --> 00:35:58,511
Still, now that we have proof,
it's better to be careful.

555
00:35:58,594 --> 00:36:01,520
Veronica has FBI contacts
from when they investigated her father.

556
00:36:01,604 --> 00:36:04,738
I'll see if she can give me
the names of those agents.

557
00:36:04,823 --> 00:36:06,620
Good thinking, Sherlock Jones.

558
00:36:06,704 --> 00:36:10,632
By the way, are you and Veronica
officially an item now?

559
00:36:13,057 --> 00:36:16,066
- Shucks, I don't know.
- Talk about being in over your crown.

560
00:36:16,986 --> 00:36:18,532
I'm holding my own.

561
00:36:18,617 --> 00:36:19,578
Mm-hm.

562
00:36:20,288 --> 00:36:22,295
[INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING]

563
00:36:28,564 --> 00:36:29,902
[BANGING ON DOOR]

564
00:36:29,985 --> 00:36:31,114
I'll get it.

565
00:36:33,957 --> 00:36:35,921
Gentlemen. You're right on time.

566
00:36:36,005 --> 00:36:37,760
They're having breakfast in Grand Hall.

567
00:36:37,844 --> 00:36:39,850
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

568
00:36:42,609 --> 00:36:46,121
Clifford Marion Blossom,
Penelope Pavlina Novikov Blossom,

569
00:36:46,706 --> 00:36:49,298
you're under arrest
for treason, conspiracy,

570
00:36:49,381 --> 00:36:52,432
and advocating for the violent overthrow
of the American government.

571
00:36:52,891 --> 00:36:55,525
The FBI is shutting down
your Project Moloch.

572
00:36:57,364 --> 00:36:58,535
[HANDCUFFS CLICK]

573
00:37:01,502 --> 00:37:03,133
You did a bad thing, Daddy.

574
00:37:03,216 --> 00:37:06,728
[JUGHEAD] <i>Over the coming days, the world
would learn about the American capitalist</i>

575
00:37:06,811 --> 00:37:09,110
<i>seduced by the Soviet sleeper agent.</i>

576
00:37:12,412 --> 00:37:14,335
<i>Operation: Project Moloch</i>

577
00:37:14,418 --> 00:37:16,759
<i>was to have been the next leg
of the arms race.</i>

578
00:37:17,553 --> 00:37:20,437
<i>From the A-bomb
to the H-bomb to the P-bomb,</i>

579
00:37:20,522 --> 00:37:21,733
<i>the palladium bomb.</i>

580
00:37:22,946 --> 00:37:25,621
<i>The U.S. believed Clifford Blossom
was developing it for them,</i>

581
00:37:25,705 --> 00:37:29,216
<i>when, in fact, his plan had been
to develop the P-bomb in Riverdale,</i>

582
00:37:29,299 --> 00:37:31,222
<i>then deliver it to Mother Russia.</i>

583
00:37:31,305 --> 00:37:35,025
<i>The FBI and the U.S. Army were credited
with foiling the plot against America,</i>

584
00:37:35,109 --> 00:37:39,205
<i>which was fine by me, as I was busy
putting the rest of the pieces together.</i>

585
00:37:39,958 --> 00:37:42,340
<i>Mr. Rayberry
must have glimpsed just enough</i>

586
00:37:42,424 --> 00:37:45,559
<i>during his job at the Blossom factory
to grow concerned.</i>

587
00:37:45,642 --> 00:37:49,948
<i>He warned us, as he always did,
with his brilliant, terrifying stories.</i>

588
00:37:50,032 --> 00:37:51,871
<i>He might have continued
flying under the radar,</i>

589
00:37:51,954 --> 00:37:54,253
<i>but then he started agitating
at Riverdale High,</i>

590
00:37:54,337 --> 00:37:57,765
<i>invoking the Supreme Court,
spooking the powers that be,</i>

591
00:37:57,848 --> 00:38:00,482
<i>prompting Mayor Blossom
to have his hitman,</i>

592
00:38:00,565 --> 00:38:02,571
<i>aka the Milkman, kill him.</i>

593
00:38:04,034 --> 00:38:06,376
<i>Ethel's folks
also paid the ultimate price.</i>

594
00:38:07,295 --> 00:38:11,600
<i>Mr. Muggs had discovered that the Blossoms
were sitting on a stockpile of palladium.</i>

595
00:38:11,684 --> 00:38:13,314
<i>That made him a threat,</i>

596
00:38:13,398 --> 00:38:15,153
<i>one that needed to be eliminated.</i>

597
00:38:15,738 --> 00:38:17,996
<i>Ethel didn't care so much
about the details,</i>

598
00:38:18,079 --> 00:38:21,967
<i>but now that she knew the complete truth
of her life, she was ready, she said,</i>

599
00:38:23,137 --> 00:38:26,397
<i>to finally start to hope again
for a better tomorrow.</i>

600
00:38:27,358 --> 00:38:29,783
Hey, Lovebug, you ready to peel out?

601
00:38:29,867 --> 00:38:31,956
["WALKIN' YOU HOME" PLAYING ON JUKEBOX]

602
00:38:32,041 --> 00:38:36,764
<i>♪ The clock is smilin'
Like a long-lost friend ♪</i>

603
00:38:37,892 --> 00:38:40,317
<i>♪ Another minute and... ♪</i>

604
00:38:40,400 --> 00:38:41,863
[DOOR OPENS, BELL JINGLES]

605
00:38:42,658 --> 00:38:44,622
[ENGINE IDLING]

606
00:38:44,705 --> 00:38:46,503
[ALICE] Are you sure about this, Ethel?

607
00:38:48,007 --> 00:38:49,554
Moving to Hollywood?

608
00:38:49,638 --> 00:38:51,435
Don't you worry, Mrs. Cooper.

609
00:38:51,519 --> 00:38:53,859
I called ahead to my friend Peter Roth.

610
00:38:53,943 --> 00:38:58,081
He saw some of Ethel's artwork
and got her a job as a storyboard artist.

611
00:38:58,164 --> 00:39:01,091
And I've arranged for Ethel
to live with one of my girlfriends

612
00:39:01,174 --> 00:39:04,100
at the most glamorous of buildings,
the El Royale.

613
00:39:04,184 --> 00:39:05,564
Thanks again, Veronica.

614
00:39:05,647 --> 00:39:06,900
My pleasure.

615
00:39:08,489 --> 00:39:09,869
Give them hell, Ethel.

616
00:39:09,952 --> 00:39:11,959
[SENTIMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING]

617
00:39:13,254 --> 00:39:16,891
Don't forget to send us your address
so I can come visit you.

618
00:39:16,974 --> 00:39:18,145
[ETHEL] I won't forget.

619
00:39:20,862 --> 00:39:22,325
Thank you for everything, Betty.

620
00:39:23,537 --> 00:39:24,582
Of course.

621
00:39:37,122 --> 00:39:41,176
I'll miss you.
You always were the best partner in crime.

622
00:39:42,138 --> 00:39:43,099
Thanks, Jughead.

623
00:39:45,356 --> 00:39:46,360
Don't be too sad.

624
00:39:47,781 --> 00:39:51,000
- We'll always have Pep Comics.
- Hopefully. We'll see.

625
00:39:55,305 --> 00:39:57,604
You are going to be just fine.

626
00:39:58,356 --> 00:39:59,777
I truly feel that.

627
00:40:00,780 --> 00:40:02,410
I hope so, Mrs. Cooper.

628
00:40:16,330 --> 00:40:17,458
[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

629
00:40:18,587 --> 00:40:20,092
[ENGINE STARTS]

630
00:40:21,847 --> 00:40:23,477
[JUGHEAD] <i>Ethel was the first of us to go.</i>

631
00:40:24,188 --> 00:40:25,776
<i>To leave Riverdale behind.</i>

632
00:40:26,738 --> 00:40:28,201
{\an8}<i>There would be others soon.</i>

633
00:40:29,288 --> 00:40:31,545
{\an8}<i>All of the pieces were falling into place.</i>

634
00:40:32,464 --> 00:40:34,805
<i>Project Moloch had failed,</i>

635
00:40:34,888 --> 00:40:38,149
<i>but it was just about time
to find out if our town would be avoiding</i>

636
00:40:38,233 --> 00:40:39,946
<i>an even greater cataclysm.</i>

637
00:40:40,030 --> 00:40:41,785
["NOTHING CAN STOP ME NOW!"
PLAYING ON STEREO]

638
00:40:41,870 --> 00:40:43,081
[VOLUME INCREASES]

639
00:40:43,165 --> 00:40:48,682
<i>♪ Nothing can stop me ♪</i>

640
00:40:48,767 --> 00:40:54,869
<i>♪ Now! ♪</i>

641
00:40:57,920 --> 00:40:59,216
[CHALK SCRATCHING]

642
00:40:59,299 --> 00:41:00,470
[BELL JINGLES]

